# AmigosIngleses - WORK vocabulary

Cuando conoces a alguien por primera vez, es bastante común que te preguntes a qué se dedica:

> What do you do? MORE COMMON
>
> What's your job?
>
> Where do you work?
>
> What do you do for a living?

Las profesiones siempre llevan _a_ o _an_:

> I'm a doctor
>
> I'm a software engineer

Lugar de trabajo:

> I work in an office
> I work in a hospital

Trabajo para una empresa:

> I work for Mobbeel
> I work for (company)

Te quedas sin trabajo:

> I'm unemployed
> I'm between jobs at the moment

Trabajo a tiempo parcial / completo

> I have a part-time job / I have a full-time job

Contrato temporal / contrato fijo

> I have a temporary contract / I have a permanent contract

El trabajo _de 9 a 5_

> I have a nine-to-five

For describe the typical full-time job, working hours from 9AM to 5PM with one hour for lunch.

Hacer prácticas en una empresa:

> I'm doing an internship
> I'm doing some work experiencies

Tengo mi propio negocio:

> I'm self-employed
> I have / I run my own business

_the rat race_ many people want to escape _the rat race_ el ciclo de vida tedioso: waking up, driving to work, working for 8 hours, coming home, in the traffic, going to sleep, waking up... this routine is called _the rat race_.

> I want to escape the rat race, for example, starting your own business or winning the lottery

Empleado:

> employee

Empleador:

> employer

Compañeros de trabajo:

> colleagues / co-workers / workmates

Jefe:

> boss / manager / supervisor

Pelota:

> brown-noser
> Don't be such a brown-noser! (nariz marrón)

Contratar:

> To hire someone
> I got hired. They hired me
> I got the job!

Quiero meter la cabez en esa empresa:

> I want to get my foot in the door
> I'm taking this job just to get my foot in the door

Ascenso:

> Get a promotion

Escalar:

> To climb the ladder
> I'm goint to work my way up (poco a poco voy a ir ascendiendo)

Empresas cazatalentos:

> headhunters (cazadores de talentos)
> Our boss has left because he was headhunted by a rival company

Pedir una subida de sueldo:

> I would like a pay rise

Tienes mucho trabajo:

> I'm completely snowed under (estoy completamente cubierto de trabajo)
> I'm swamped at work (estoy inundado en el trabajo)

Mi jefe está todo el tiempo encima de mí, me está presionando

> Mi boss is breathing down mi neck (mi jefe me está respirando detrás)

Me han despedido:

> I've been fired (USA)
> I've been sacked (UK)
> They sacked me because I arrived late

Pero si la compañía tiene problemas:

> The let me gone

Te quieres ir de la empresa:

> I've come to hand in my resignation
> I'm handing in my notice

Me voy a jubilar:

> I'm going to retire
> I'm retired

Ejercicios:

_Un día como hoy, en un año, estaré jubilado_

> This time, next year, I'll be retired

_Mi hermana es dentista y mi hermano es ingeniero_

> My sister is a dentist and my brother is an engineer

_Yo era periodista pero me despidieron_

> I was a journalist but they sacked me
> I was a journalist but I was sacked

_Tengo un empleo a tiempo parcial como camarera_

> I've got a part-time job as a waitress

_Perdona que no hemos estado en contacto, hemos estado hasta arriba de trabajo_

> Sorry I haven't been in touch, I've been swamped at work

_Lo siento no puedo hablar ahora, mi jefe está encima de mí en el trabajo_

> Sorry, I can't talk now, my boss is breathing down mi neck at work
